------------------------------------------------------------<br>
<br>
Of course. But there is a strong sentiment here of &quot;all these kids need is a good whooping,&quot; which is really hard to get behind. Parents obviously have a huge role in their children's lives, that can't be denied. What I can't agree with is that there is some magical sort of &quot;right way&quot; and &quot;wrong way&quot; to raise your children. That school violence can be attributed 100% to &quot;wrong&quot; parenting. Children grow up in crack houses and turn out ok. Kids that have the perfect parents turn out messed up. Some kids are psychologically messed up in ways that aren't anybody's &quot;fault.&quot; Kids are resilient enough to where small variations in parenting methods are not going to result in a completely corrupted set of morals. If you look at things across cultures, we don't all raise children the same way. Some cultures are much stricter, some are much looser, but we don't see a culture of axe murderers out there because the kids were raised a certain way. I tend to think that unless you outright abuse your children, your kids are probably going to turn out decent. Not to say that parents aren't influential, they are, but children, by nature, are highly adaptive.<br>
<br>
Although school violence is highly publicized, the majority of children don't commit violent crimes. There are far more normal children out there than there are killers, far too many for &quot;lack of discipline&quot; to be a reasonable answer. I would be interested to see case studies on these children and see what kind of homes they were raised in, but I wouldn't be surprised if there weren't any obvious answers to be found in the parenting, something you could point to and say &quot;oh, well there's where they went wrong,&quot; unless it was a case of obvious abuse (not talking spankings here. I think there are more effective ways of raising children, but I'm talking about heavy beatings, verbal abuse, sexual abuse, the kind of stuff that is severely damaging to a child's psyche). Thinking otherwise may make us feel better about how we raise our children, make us feel a certain sense of security, but in the end parents who raise their children in the best possible way still sometimes end up with the worst possible outcome. <br>
<br>
Trabious<br>
